post_text:
Books! Books! Books! Books!
All across Kirby’s Mill,
everywhere you look,
students were reading books.

It was a contest,
don’t you know.
Read the most books
and watch your chances grow.

Students accepted the challenge,
visited the library in flocks.
Books were checked out
and yet the shelves were always stocked.

Sports, Space and Ships
Animals
The Ocean
Travel and trips.

The library was busy.
So many students,
so many books,
Mrs. King was surely dizzy.

And on Friday Kirby’s celebrated
all the hard work the students demonstrated.
It was time to read the tally,
It was time for the Read Across America pep rally.

Kirby's Mill Elementary School

post_text: On Thursday night, nearly 600 students, parents and teachers attended a forum at the Lenape High School Auditorium designed to inform the community about the NJ State funding formula which will result in the loss of more than $23 million in state funding for our schools. Dr. Birnbohm, Dr. Del Rossi, Michael Harris and Christine Vespe all spoke at the meeting encouraging action to help protect the integrity of our schools and school programs. To find out more you can follow Support Our Students (SOS) on twitter @nj_sos. You can also sign the online petition to encourage Governor Murphy to re-examine the impact of the state funding formula at www.lrhsd.org/SOSpetition.

post_text:
It was Careers Day at Memorial on Thursday. Eighth grade students had the opportunity to hear keynote addresses from three Memorial graduates: Doug Holcombe (who kicked off his presentation with a group selfie), P.T. Ranere and Megan Flanagan. The theme of their message: Keep an open mind — life may not always take you in the direction you think you are going to go.
After the keynote speakers, students attended breakout sessions to hear from local professionals that represented a range of career possibilities. Among those that presented sessions were representatives from the Flyers, Phillies, the US Postal Service, the Medford Police Department, Rowan University, medical and mental health care professionals as well as many others.
Thank you to Ms. Crivello, Ms. Moorhead and Ms. Ronayne who organized the event for the eighth graders!

post_text:
Welcome all incoming kindergartners and their families! Kirby's Mill Elementary School hosted the annual Kindergarten Information Night led by Supervisor of Instruction, Dr. Asbury, and Kirby's Mill Kindergarten teacher, Ms. Slocum. This night was the first of three events designed to inform families just entering Medford Township Public Schools about our Kindergarten curriculum.
Superintendent, Dr. Del Rossi, started the evening by welcoming families and introducing our staff and then parents had the opportunity to visit classrooms for curriculum centered breakout sessions with kindergarten teachers from the whole district.
Parents were also treated to door prizes and insulated tote bags generously donated by Murphy's Fresh Markets.
The next important, not-to-miss event is Race Car Night on March 11, 2020.
If you missed the Information Night or want to review information provided check out our district Kindergarten in Training website. This site has important dates as well as helpful videos.
https://sites.google.com/medford.k12.nj.us/kindergartners-in-training/home

post_text: Yesterday, Dr. Emmanuel Ndiema, Head of Archaeology for the National Museum of Kenya, spoke to Mr. Del Rossi's 6th grade Social Studies class about growing up in Kenya. Dr. Ndiema discussed archeological finds that have been made in Kenya and shared artifacts and cultural pieces from his tribe. A special thanks to former Medford teacher (and current substitute) Ruth Reed for putting us in touch with Dr. Ndiema.

Tuesday night Haines held its Science Fun Night. Parents and students rotated through centers that featured experiments with, among other things, optics and milk. One experiment explored the magnetic properties of iron and required a volunteer to donate a crisp dollar bill to be blended into a pulp. *wink wink*
Once the mash was created and the slush poured into a zip lock bag, students ran a magnet over the mixture to see how much iron they could attract. Watch your wallet if your children tell you they want to try that one at home!

post_text: On Friday, teachers became students while participating in a full day of professional development. The day began with small study groups on topics such as Reducing Anxiety in Our Students and Guided Math. The morning continued with teachers choosing from over 30 interactive workshops led by their peers. Sessions included learning how to use digital programs such as Adobe Spark, Flipgrid and QR codes to capture their student’s attention. Other offerings included Guided Reading, Science, and Math workshops. Professional development days like Friday, contain valuable reflection time with colleagues and is crucial in helping teachers implement new ideas and practices.

On Wednesday, April 17, 2019 four out of the five Medford Township Public Schools elementary schools hosted Kindergarten Round-Up. Kindergarten Round-Up introduces in-coming kindergarten children and their parents to their home school. Parents hear from school personnel including the principal, guidance counselor, nurse, and school librarian who share pertinent information about the school community and entrance into kindergarten. They get a look at what life is like in the kindergarten classroom via video presentations and photo montages, as well as hear from the kindergarten teachers themselves. While the parents take in information and interact through a Q&A time, the future kinders are treated to a stint in a kindergarten classroom. The highlight of the day is a ride on a school bus. For many, this is a first-time experience that brings excitement and smiles. Kindergarten Round-Up is a favorite day for all Medford staff. We look forward every year to welcoming our youngest learners into our schools!

post_text: Aspiring Engineers presenting a Foot Orthosis for patients with Cerebral Palsy in their Project Lead the Way class at Memorial. post_text: On Wednesday, March 27, 2019 Medford students participated in the 1st Annual Future Chef’s Challenge. Future Chef is a national culinary competition created by Sodexo that is open to Elementary students. There were 7 finalists chosen out of many entries received from 5 Medford Elementary Schools. As an added bonus, our competition is just one of many local competitions that Sodexo will be orchestrating across the country in March. Thanks to Sodexo and Maureen Casey for bringing the experience to Medford. We want to congratulate each and every finalist in the competition. This years winners are Mia and Madeline with their Keto Taco Cups!

At the MTPS BOE meeting on Monday January 28, 2019,the Medford Education Foundation announced the recipients of grant funding. All of the grants awarded will serve to support classroom instruction and enhance our student’s educational programming. A huge thank you to MEF for their outstanding efforts in supporting our students and community.

Pictured from right to left, Ms. Pam Scheller, President-MEF, Ms. Kara McGough, PE Teacher - Haines, Ms. Ally Hampton, Science Teacher - Memorial, Ms. Michele Loughlin, Media Center Specialist - Memorial, Ms. Amy LePage, Occupational Therapist - Allen, Mr. John Karakashian, Principal - Chairville (Standing in for Mr. Adam Keagy, PE Teacher), Mr. Tony Hurst, Multimedia Technician - MTPS, and Mr. Chris Murphy, MEF -Treasurer.

On Wednesday, October 10, 2018, Memorial's 'Girls Matter!' Classes & Student Council hosted the 14th Annual Pink Day and Pink Walk for the cure. Students from 6th, 7th, & 8th grades dressed in pink i honor of Breast Cancer Awareness Month. After school, students, parents, and others from Medford and surrounding communities met at Memorial's Track to raise money for awareness.
